<ArticleLayout
  title="Bassinet vs Cot: Which One Makes Sense First?"
  description="A practical Australian guide comparing bassinets and cots, including space, budget, safety checks, mattress fit, age suitability and what to consider before buying."
  category="Nursery & Kids"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="7 minute read"
  image="/images/Nursery-kids.webp"
  imageAlt="A tidy nursery with a cot, change area and practical baby storage"
>
  <p>
    Choosing between a bassinet and a cot is really a question about your home, your budget,
    the early weeks and how long you want each item to be useful. Both can make sense, but
    neither is automatically the right first choice for every family.
  </p>

  <h2>The difference at a glance</h2>
  <ComparisonTable rows={comparisonRows} caption="Comparison of a bassinet, cot and using both" />

  <h2>How a bassinet differs</h2>
  <p>
    A bassinet is a smaller sleep space usually intended for younger babies. Families often
    consider one because it can be easier to place near an adult bed or move within the home,
    depending on the design.
  </p>

  <h2>How a cot differs</h2>
  <p>
    A cot is a larger sleep space that can usually be used for longer. It takes more room,
    but it may reduce the need to change sleep setups after the first few months.
  </p>

  <h2>When a bassinet may suit</h2>
  <p>
    A bassinet may suit if you have limited bedroom space, want a compact early setup or need
    something easier to place close by. Check age, weight and size limits carefully because
    bassinets are generally outgrown sooner than cots.
  </p>

  <h2>When a cot may suit</h2>
  <p>
    A cot may suit if you have enough room for safe placement and want a sleep
    space from the start. Check mattress fit, assembly, clearances, ventilation and current
    Australian safety guidance before use.
  </p>

  <h2>When using both may make sense</h2>
  <p>
    Some families use a bassinet in the early weeks and set up a cot for the nursery. This can
    be practical, but it means planning for storage, extra sheets and a transition later.
  </p>

  <h2>Space and budget considerations</h2>
  <p>
    Measure your room before comparing options. Include door swings, bedside access, windows,
    heaters, curtains, power points and walking space. A compact item is only useful if it can
    be used safely and comfortably in your actual room.
  </p>
  <p>
    Budget should include linen, mattress compatibility, replacement parts if needed and the
    likely length of use. A cot can cost more up front, while a bassinet may have a shorter
    useful life.
  </p>

  <h2>Checks that matter for sleep safety</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Check current Australian safety guidance before choosing a sleep space.</li>
    <li>Follow manufacturer instructions for assembly, use, cleaning and age limits.</li>
    <li>Check mattress fit. Gaps, soft surfaces or incorrect sizing can create risks.</li>
    <li>Check age, weight and size suitability before first use and as the baby grows.</li>
    <li>Check recalls and safety notices where relevant, especially for second-hand items.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Where families can get caught out</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Choosing an item before measuring the room.</li>
    <li>Assuming every bassinet is suitable for overnight sleep.</li>
    <li>Using a mattress that does not fit the exact sleep space.</li>
    <li>Forgetting that babies can outgrow compact sleep spaces quickly.</li>
    <li>Keeping instructions, labels or safety information separate from the item.</li>
  </ul>

  <RelatedGuidesBlock guides={relatedGuides} />
  <FAQBlock items={faqs} />
</ArticleLayout>
